entries.content: I’ve been feeling really overwhelmed lately. There’s so much to do with exams, work, and personal stuff all piling up. My mind keeps racing, and it’s hard to focus. I wish I could slow down or find a way to feel less anxious. I hope tomorrow will be better.
entries.reflection: There's fear present in your writing. This emotion helps us identify potential threats, but sometimes it can overestimate risks. Try to distinguish between helpful caution and limiting anxiety.

entries.content:
Lately, I’ve been feeling a lot of frustration. It hit me hard last week when a project I’d been working on for weeks suddenly faced unexpected setbacks. I felt powerless and worried that all my effort was going to be wasted. The frustration bubbled up quickly and was hard to shake off.

To cope, I decided to take a step back and give myself some space to breathe. I went for a walk outside and tried to focus on small things that brought me calm—the sound of birds, the fresh air, and the sunlight. I also talked to a close friend about what I was feeling, which helped me feel less alone and more understood. Eventually, I reminded myself that setbacks are a normal part of growth and that I can use this as a learning experience rather than a failure.
entries.reflection: I notice sadness in your entry. Remember that all emotions, including difficult ones, are part of the human experience. Be gentle with yourself as you process these feelings.
